---
import Header from "@/components/Articles/Header.astro";
import Picture from "@/components/Picture.astro";
import Chapter from "@/layouts/Chapter.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Articles/Header.astro";
import Picture from "@/components/Picture.astro";
import Prose from "@/components/Articles/Prose.astro";
import ExternalLink from "@/components/Articles/ExternalLink.astro";
import Keyword from "@/components/Articles/Keyword.astro";
import MonkeySnippet from "./_components/MonkeySnippet.astro";
import LetTokens from "./_components/LetTokens.astro";
import OperationPrecendence from "./_components/OperationPrecendence.astro";
import MakeInterpreter from "./_components/MakeInterpreter.astro";
import MakeExecuter from "./_components/MakeExecuter.astro";
import RunningTests from "./_components/RunningTests.astro";
---

<Chapter>
  <div class="md:w-3/4 lg:w-2/3 flex flex-col items-center">
    <Header
      year="2024"
      readingTime="5 minute"
      codeLink="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter"
    >
      Teaching a Machine to Understand: Inside a Custom Programming Language
    </Header>

    <Picture
      class="appear w-full md:w-3/4 aspect-square sm:aspect-video border-4"
      loading="eager"
      src="/images/monkey.avif"
      alt="Language"
      size={514}
    />
  </div>
  <Prose>
    <h3 class="fraunces">
      Following Thorsten Ball's Writing An Interpreter In Go
    </h3>

    <p>
      I've always been drawn to <strong>books</strong> as a way to learn, and at
      some point I found myself wanting a serious project involving <strong
        >parsers</strong
      > — something that wasn't going to feel like a toy, something that would demand
      real focus over a long period of time. So I did what felt natural: I searched
      for a book about parsers and Go. <ExternalLink
        text="Writing An Interpreter In Go"
        href="https://interpreterbook.com/"
      /> by <strong>Thorsten Ball</strong> was the first result that came up. I picked
      it up, and about six months later I had built a fully <strong
        >functional programming language</strong
      > from scratch — no libraries, no shortcuts, just Go and a much deeper understanding
      of how interpreters work under the hood. This is the story of that project:
      <ExternalLink
        text="dyxgou/interpreter"
        href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter"
      />.
    </p>
    <h3 class="fraunces">The Monkey Programming Language</h3>

    <p>
      The language implemented here is <strong>Monkey</strong> — a small, expressive
      language invented by <strong>Thorsten Ball</strong> which implementes a rich
      set of features.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><Keyword word="Integer" /> and <Keyword word="Booleans" />.</li>
      <li><Keyword word="String" /> manipulation</li>
      <li>Variables and bindings (<Keyword word="let" /> statements)</li>
      <li>First-class and higher-order functions</li>
      <li>Closures</li>
      <li>Arrays and hash maps</li>
      <li>
        A built-in library (e.g., <Keyword word="len" />, <Keyword
          word="print"
        />, <Keyword word="first" />, <Keyword word="last" />, <Keyword
          word="push"
        />, <Keyword word="pop" />)
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>Here's a taste of what <strong>Monkey code</strong> looks like:</p>

    <MonkeySnippet />

    <p>
      You can find <strong>more examples</strong> in the <ExternalLink
        text="example/"
        href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter/tree/main/example"
      /> folder of the repository.
    </p>

    <h3 class="fraunces">Architecture: How the Interpreter Works</h3>

    <p>
      The interpreter is structured as a classic <strong>pipeline</strong> — source
      code <strong>enters</strong> one end, and computed results <strong
        >come out</strong
      > the other. There are four core components, each with a clearly defined responsibility.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        The <Keyword word="Lexer" /> (<ExternalLink
          text="src/lexer"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter/tree/main/src/lexer"
        />)

        <p>
          The <Keyword word="Lexer" /> is the very first stage of interpretation.
          Its job is to read <strong>raw source code</strong> — and convert it into
          a stream of <Keyword word="" />. A token is a <strong
            >meaningful unit</strong
          > of the language: a <strong>keyword</strong> like <Keyword
            word="let"
          /> or <Keyword word="fn" />, an operator like <Keyword word="+" /> or <Keyword
            word="==,"
          />
          an integer, an identifier, or a delimiter like <Keyword word="{" /> and
          <Keyword word="}" />. For example, the code <Keyword
            word="let x = 5 + 3;"
          />
          gets <strong>transformed</strong> into a sequence like:
        </p>

        <LetTokens />

        <p>
          The <Keyword word="Lexer" /> doesn't care whether the code makes sense
          — that's someone else's problem. It only cares about <strong
            >recognizing</strong
          > and <strong>categorizing</strong> individual pieces of text.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        The <Keyword word="AST" /> (<ExternalLink
          text="src/ast"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter/tree/main/src/ast"
        />)

        <p>
          Before the <Keyword word="Parser" /> can do anything useful, we need a
          <strong>data structure</strong> to represent the shape of the program.
          That's the <strong>Abstract Syntax Tree</strong> (<Keyword
            word="AST"
          />). It's a <strong>tree</strong> of nodes where each node represents a
          syntactic construct: a <Keyword word="Statement" />, an <Keyword
            word="Expression"
          />, a <Keyword word="Function" />, an <Keyword
            word="infix operation"
          />, and so on.
        </p>

        <p>
          For example, the expression <Keyword word="5 + 3 * 2" /> doesn't get treated
          as a <strong>flat list</strong> — it gets structured as a tree that encodes
          <strong>operator precedence</strong>:
        </p>

        <OperationPrecendence />
        <p>
          The <strong>AST package</strong> defines all the <Keyword
            word="Node"
          />
          types and ensures every node in the tree implements a <strong
            >common interface</strong
          >, making it easy for the <Keyword word="Parser" /> and <Keyword
            word="Evaluator"
          /> to work with them <strong>uniformly</strong>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        The <Keyword word="Parser" /> (<ExternalLink
          text="src/parser"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter/tree/main/src/parser"
        />)

        <p>
          The <Keyword word="Parser" /> takes the <Keyword word="Token" /> stream
          from the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> and builds the <Keyword
            word="AST"
          />. This is the most <strong>intellectually interesting</strong> component
          of the whole project.
        </p>

        <p>
          The implementation follows a <strong>Pratt parser</strong> (also called
          a top-down operator precedence parser), a technique described elegantly
          in the book. The key insight of a <strong>Pratt parser</strong> is that
          each token type can have <strong>prefix</strong> and <strong
            >infix</strong
          > parse functions associated with it. When the parser encounters a <Keyword
            word="Token"
          />, it calls the appropriate <strong>parsing function</strong>, which
          returns an <Keyword word="AST" /> node. This approach handles operator
          precedence <strong>naturally</strong> and <strong>elegantly</strong>,
          without resorting to complicated grammar rules.
        </p>

        <p>
          The parser also performs <strong>syntax validation</strong> — if the token
          stream doesn't form a valid Monkey program, the parser <strong
            >reports errors</strong
          > rather than silently producing garbage.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        The <Keyword word="Evaluator" /> (<ExternalLink
          text="src/evaluator"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter/tree/main/src/evaluator"
        />)

        <p>
          The <Keyword word="Evaluator" /> is where the <strong
            >magic happens</strong
          >. It walks the
          <Keyword word="AST" /> recursively — a tree-walking interpreter — and computes
          the value of every <Keyword word="Node" /> it <strong>visits</strong>.
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            An <Keyword word="IntegerLiteral" /> node evaluates to its <strong
              >numeric value</strong
            >.
          </li>
          <li>
            An <Keyword word="InfixExpression" /> node evaluates both sides and applies
            the operator.
          </li>
          <li>
            An <Keyword word="IfExpression" /> evaluates the <strong
              >condition</strong
            >, then takes the appropriate branch.
          </li>
          <li>
            A <Keyword word="FunctionLiteral" /> captures the outer <strong
              >environment</strong
            >.
          </li>
          <li>
            A <Keyword word="CallExpression" /> extends <strong
              >the environment</strong
            >, binds arguments, and <strong>evaluates</strong> the function body.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          The <Keyword word="Evaluator" /> also manages the <Keyword
            word="Object"
          /> system — every value in Monkey <strong
            >(integers, strings, booleans, arrays, hashes, functions, null)</strong
          > is represented as a Go struct implementing a common <Keyword
            word="Object"
          /> interface. This makes it easy to pass values around and <strong
            >pattern-match</strong
          >
          on their types.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        The <Keyword word="REPL" /> (<ExternalLink
          text="src/repl"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter/tree/main/src/repl"
        />)

        <p>
          All of this comes together in a <strong>Read-Eval-Print Loop</strong>.
          The <Keyword word="REPL" /> reads a line of <Keyword word="code" />,
          runs it through the full pipeline <strong
            >(lexer → parser → evaluator)</strong
          >, and prints the result. You can launch it with a single <strong
            >make command:
          </strong>
        </p>

        <MakeInterpreter />

        <p>Or execute a Monkey source file directly:</p>

        <MakeExecuter />
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="Testing" />

        <p>
          This project was built following <strong
            >Test Driven Development (TDD)</strong
          >, as guided by the book itself. Every component was written
          <strong>test-first</strong> — before implementing a feature, leading to
          an extensive test suite where every major component — the <Keyword
            word="Lexer"
          />, <Keyword word="Parser" />, <Keyword word="AST" />, and <Keyword
            word="Evaluator"
          /> — has dedicated tests that verify correct behavior across a wide range
          of inputs, including <strong>edge cases</strong> and <strong
            >error conditions</strong
          >.
        </p>

        <RunningTests />
      </li>
    </ol>

    <ol>
      <li>
        Repository: <ExternalLink
          text="github.com/dyxgou/interpreter"
          href="https://github.com/dyxgou/interpreter"
        />
      </li>
      <li>
        Book: <ExternalLink
          text="Writing An Interpreter In Go by Thorsten Ball"
          href="https://interpreterbook.com/"
        />
      </li>
    </ol>
  </Prose>
</Chapter>
